1. Operating System (Windows 11):

Download: Visit the official Microsoft website (https://www.microsoft.com/software-download/windows11) and download the Windows 11 installation media (likely an ISO file).
Create Bootable USB: Use a tool like Rufus to create a bootable USB drive with the Windows 11 ISO.
Installation:
Restart your computer and enter the BIOS/UEFI settings.
Set your boot priority to boot from the USB drive.
Follow the on-screen instructions to install Windows 11.
2. Text Editor/IDE (Visual Studio Code):

Download: Go to the Visual Studio Code website (https://code.visualstudio.com/Download) and choose the appropriate installer for your system (Windows).
Installation:
Run the installer.
Follow the installation wizard's instructions.
Choose the components you want to install (e.g., Python extension).
3. Version Control System (Git & GitHub):

Install Git: Download Git from the official website (https://git-scm.com/) and follow the installation instructions.
GitHub Account: Create a free account on GitHub (https://github.com/).
Repository Setup:
Create a new repository on GitHub for your project.
Open your project folder in Visual Studio Code.
Open the integrated terminal (Ctrl+`).
Run the following commands:
Bash
git init       # Initialize a Git repository in your project folder
git add .      # Add all files to the staging area
git commit -m "Initial commit"  # Commit the changes with a message
git remote add origin <repository_url>  # Link your local repo to GitHub
git push -u origin master   # Push your code to GitHub
Use code with caution.
content_copy
Replace <repository_url> with your repository's address from GitHub.

4. Programming Languages (Python):

Download: Get the latest Python version from the official website (https://www.python.org/).
Installation:
Run the installer.
Make sure to check the box to "Add Python to PATH" during installation.
Follow the on-screen instructions.
5. Package Manager (pip):

Pip is usually included when you install Python.
To verify, open your terminal and run pip --version.
6. Database (MySQL):

Download: Go to the MySQL Downloads page (https://dev.mysql.com/downloads/windows/installer/5.7.html) and choose the appropriate installer.
Installation:
Run the installer.
Follow the setup wizard, choosing the "Developer Default" setup type.
Set a root password and remember it.
7. Development Environments (Optional):

Docker (Recommended): If you're going to be working on projects that require specific environments or isolation, learn how to use Docker. It's a powerful tool.
Virtual Machines: If Docker is too complex for your current needs, you can use virtual machines (e.g., VirtualBox, VMware) to create isolated environments.
8. Extensions & Plugins:

Visual Studio Code:
Open the Extensions tab (Ctrl+Shift+X).
Search for and install extensions like:
Python
MySQL
GitLens
Prettier (for code formatting)
9. Documentation:

Create a detailed document that includes:
Each step you followed
Screenshots for visual reference
Any errors you encountered and how you resolved them
Additional Tips:

Customization: Customize Visual Studio Code's settings to your preferences (themes, fonts, etc.).
Shell (Optional): Consider learning how to use a more powerful terminal like Git Bash or Windows Terminal.
